Replying to @bsstahl

The value proposition of unit testing is to give us the confidence to "refactor ruthlessly". The fact that a section of code is "covered" does little if anything to provide that confidence. #TDD #UnitTest

Wed Nov 13 16:37:27 +0000 2019

Replying to @bsstahl

Pushing for "Test Coverage" just masks the fact that our tests are not covering the use cases. Improving test coverage will not help quality. In fact, it likely hurts quality due to the aformentioned masking. #TDD #UnitTest

RT @NDC_Conferences: Just added @bsstahl talk "Eliminating Hidden Dangers to Your Applications Patterns for Reliable Systems" on our YouTub…

Thu Dec 23 16:27:22 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

Great question, and thanks for letting me know I wasn't clear enough on that. It is a rather important point.

Mon Dec 27 21:06:50 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

If either service fails when they are in separate contexts, that service can simply be retried until it succeeds (as long as the failure is transient). This means the functionality is now eventually-consistent, but both actions will succeed as long as the failure is not a perma

Mon Dec 27 21:07:47 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

nant one. This also means that your service does exactly what you need if the failure is permanent. Ie, if some of the input data is bad, the fix is to submit fixed data to that service. No need to write special code to only do that part of the process.

Mon Dec 27 21:10:01 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

Both services are now clear about what they are supposed to do and failures within them are consistent, easy to profile, and easy to remediate.

Mon Dec 27 21:12:38 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

Plus, I think you'll find that, once used to it, it isn't an increase in complexity at all. In fact, it makes it much easier for teams since 2 people can work on the separate services independently, and deploy and scale them independently as well.

Mon Dec 27 21:20:02 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

Depends on your plans. If you need to publish-or-perish, or have no reasonable expectation that it will be maintained by a team, have many updates, or need to scale, then build whatever you are most comfortable with, abstracted or not.

Wed Dec 29 15:19:13 +0000 2021

Replying to @luxaritas

If you do expect any of the above conditions, build for maintainability or be aware of the tech debt you are creating and plan for it. They're your nights and weekends being sacrificed.

Wed Dec 29 15:20:06 +0000 2021

Replying to @NookTtocs

A common misconception, but I find it unlikely that you've never:

  • Tested logic in isolation (w/o the DB)
  • Changed from a file to an RDBMS
  • Added an API in front of a DB
  • Added a cache in front of a store
  • Moved from local to a cloud DB

all of which are changing the DB.

Tue Jan 04 13:49:46 +0000 2022

Replying to @NookTtocs, @jeremydmiller and @NookTtocs

Perhaps you mean something closer to "...you almost never change from one RDBMS to another...". i.e. nobody goes from Oracle to SQL Server or vice-versa. I'd just hate for that to get confused with the many reasons for abstracting data stores.

Tue Jan 04 14:57:41 +0000 2022

Replying to @jeremydmiller and @NookTtocs

100% agree with the 2nd statement, disagree with the 1st. See earlier msg for better list, but one example is adding a caching layer. Happens all the time, different data store.

Tue Jan 04 15:10:32 +0000 2022

Replying to @NookTtocs and @jeremydmiller

I prefer to replace my call to the existing implementation, with a new one (same interface) that returns values from the cache on hit, and calls the previous implementation on miss. Single Responsibility.

About the Author

Barry S. Stahl (he/him/his) - Barry is a .NET Software Engineer who has been creating business solutions for enterprise customers since the mid 1980s. Barry is also an Election Integrity Activist, baseball and hockey fan, husband of one genius and father of another, and a 40 year resident of Phoenix Arizona USA. When Barry is not traveling around the world to speak at Conferences, Code Camps and User Groups or to participate in GiveCamp events, he spends his days as the Principal Engineer for AZNerds.net in Phoenix AZ and his nights thinking about the next AZGiveCamp event where software creators come together to build websites and apps for some great non-profit organizations.

For more information, see: About Barry.

Barry has started delivering in-person talks again now that numerous mechanisms for protecting our communities from Covid-19 are available. He will, of course, still entertain opportunities to speak online. Please him if you would like him to deliver one of his talks at your event, either online or in-person.

Contact Barry Barry's Community Speaker page
